<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12030i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12030i">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12030i"> 30(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> in pace (oubliette)</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">D&apos;apr&egrave;s eux, il faisait plus clair au fond des mines de Sib&eacute;rie que dans ces puisards tortueux, ces oubliettes &eacute;troites, ces abominables in pace, o&ugrave; les moines, affirmaient-ils, pr&eacute;cipitaient par milliers ces lamentables et <font color="green">[104]</font> innocentes victimes du despotisme royal et du fanatisme religieux. <br><font color="green">[According to them, there was more light at the bottom of the mines of Siberia than in these tortuous pits, the narrow dungeons, the abominable in pace, where the monks, they claimed, threw by the thousands the pitiful and innocent victims of royal despotism and religious fanaticism.]</font> <small> &Eacute;tienne Dupont, <a name="LMSM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LMSM"><cite title="source">Les l&eacute;gendes du Mont-Saint-Michel</cite></a> (1924) 104-5</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Oubliette. A secret dungeon (literally, a place where you are forgotten), access to which was gained only through a trap-door above. In monasteries, dungeons were called <i>in pace</i> (from the Latin <i>requiescat in pace</i>, let him rest in peace). See 033(h) and 059(b). </mm> </dd></dl>
